Grateful for every mile. 

21 years ago today (enough time to have born a human who would be legal to drink! 🤣) I went out on a run that ended much sooner than expected when I fractured my medial tibia plateau head. 

Ah, such fond memories. 

While the recovery was brutal and I didn't run for 8 years, and I wouldn't wish something like this on anyone, I am thankful for the human and coach this injury helped shape me to become. I know, without a doubt, I wouldn't be who I am nor would I view the lense of sport the same without having gone through something like this. 

We all have a battle we have fought or are fighting. We all have experienced struggles in our journey. Mine just so happened to leave me with a few physical scars and a deeper appreciation for my body, and for every single mile I've taken since I was able to come back from this. This injury has started to slow me down some, but it will never take away the joy that running and exploring on my own two feet has given me.

(Photos 2 and 3 are when the last of my two 1.5# screws were removed in 2014. 💪 maybe I should make a pair of earrings?!)

..

Oh hey! Just a reminder that using RPE when trail running means that you are tuning into your rate of effort, which changes and adapts with everything from how you felt going into the run (sleep, stress, fatigue etc) and your experience on the run (ascent, descent, flat, technical or smooth and flowy). Some days, you're climbing 1000' a mile, and other days, you're cruising on sweet single-track or gravel roads.
That means your pace may vary quite a bit (esp compared to road running) based on the intended RPE for the day and where you're running. And that's the point! Let's please, please, please normalize s l o w i n g down on those easy 5/6 days. And maybe even slowing down a bit more. Ego has no place out there on the trails.  Find your sustainable effort and go with it, tuning into the feedback your body is giving you and adjusting accordingly.

Here are some examples of the averages from some of my most recent runs (all RPE 5-7), sharing this in the hopes that you, too, may embrace the fact that pace changes when you base your training on effort and the course/conditions you're running on. 💪

Reflections from WSER. 

It's been just over a week since #WSER and I still can't completely put into words (but you all know I am going to try!) how amazing my experience was. I have never had a race feel so right from start to finish, even when things got hard. Especially when things got hard. Here are a few of my takeaways that really stand out: 

From the second I heard my name called in the lottery, I committed to having an EXPERIENCE vs an event. I can honestly say I have never entered a race where some part of me didn't hold a specific time or performance goal. And while I know this is a big driver for many people (even myself at times) I also know how the disappointment of not meeting a specific time goal can suck some of the joy out of an event. And after waiting so. very. long. for this, I did not want my states to be anything but a celebration. Of joy made corporeal through my footfalls. I wanted to soak every moment in. I distinctly remember the first time someone asked me my time goal, and I replied without hesitation - 29:59:59. I wanted to make it to both the start and finish line, and I wanted JOY to be a driver of this, not a back seat observer to a goal. States may very well be my last 100 based on how my osteoarthritis is progressing, so I wanted to make it one to truly remember. And did I ever! 

I can not explain the true joy and freedom I felt in not having any time goal. Of just being present and soaking up the day. I cannot recall ANY race where my memories are so vivid. Where I was so engaged. So mentally with it and positive. This is the best gift I have ever given myself when it comes to a race approach. 

 Running on Effort and staying Positive - I have never managed my effort (look ma, no early race blow ups!) or stayed so positive throughout. Even when the snow (and my tailbone taking a nice crack at mile 7.50!) slowed me down. My mantra was "presence and patience." I knew if I could keep moving and move from aid station to aid station, I would finish. I never doubted that. So that is exactly what I did. (Continued in comments)

New gym! First lifting session post 100! Fun, fun! 

Recovering post 100 looks different to each person, and I always listen to my body for both what it needs and when it needs it...and then I add a dose of common sense. 

I WANTED to run 2 days post states, but my tailbone was like "nah, girl" so I walked. And ate. And slept. A lot. And spent the weekend cleaning up my new gym space. It's still a work in progress, but I'm so excited about the possibilities of this area. 

Today I wanted to get back into some EASY and post event appropriate strength. This included:

✨️ front rack hold Banded toe taps

✨️heel elevated ball braced goblet squats 

✨️ball braced push ups

✨️overchest hold marching bridges 

✨️ tall kneeling Atlas pressses

The ball and band in their respective exercises add a great tactile cue to help me focus on specific muscles when moving, and also help with some extra core stimulus.  All in all a great first session back, and I'm pleased with how good things are recovering. 

I'm very excited to start lifting heavy again in the coming weeks, and have that be a solid focus as summer turns to fall, but for now, I'm going to enjoy my recovery process and giving my body both what it needs and wants. 

Happy Wednesday!

Sometimes we are so caught up in the "what's next" we don't truly appreciate the now. 

Food for thought for your next recovery period:
It's ok to slow down.
It's ok to not have a "next" plan right away.
It's ok to savor the quiet "in between" of goals.
It's ok to rest.

Really.

One thing that I have gained over time (through a lot of hard work on myself untangling old mindsets and beliefs) is that I am FAR more interested in WHAT body can do than HOW my body looks. 

This machine has taken me on so many adventures and accomplished so many things. The chassis has taken its far share of hits and damage - some just a product of time, others due to unfortunate poor "user care" in my late teens and early twenties - but the engine is strong. She still lets me do all the things I want to do. I am so, so thankful for that. 
We hang in there, her and I. We do the adventures. We hold on to the memories of those adventures past. We dream of what's next.
And none of that involves what size I'll be or how we will look in a swimsuit. 
Nah, we got dirt to play in and mountains to climb! Rivers to swim in and back porches to sip coffee off of while the sun rises, and wild blackberries to pick until our fingers are sticky.
Those things don't come with a size or shape. 
For me or you. 

So I play with strength as I unfurl through this post 100 recovery. Not exploding like a firework onto the next thing, but rather enjoying the slow unwinding of the now. Doing things now that I enjoy that make me stronger for tomorrow, whatever it brings. No size required. 

✔️DB RDLs
✔️Decline Push Ups to elevated down dog
✔️DB Reverse Lunges 
✔️DB Crossover Rotating Rows
✔️DB Sumo Deadlifts 
✔️DB Hang Clean/Press 

Happy moving, friends.

You can do more with what you have and where you are than you think you can. 
Pick things up.
Put them down.
Push things away.
Carry them. 
Hold things in different ways
And on different sides of your body.

Your body only knows time under tension, loading, and moving in different ways under said loads. So if you don't have a BB, use DBs. Not heavy enough? Do more sets/reps, pause, and hold for more time. Don't let the notion that something has to be perfect to be beneficial or worthy of your time. 
Don't let the lack of one tool or another be a barrier. Use what you have. Get creative. Be curious. Have fun! 

✔️90/90 with @stickmobility pull apart and rotation
✔️Long Lever Bridge with Plate Pullover
✔️Hex Bar Deadlift
✔️Push Ups
✔️B Stance Single Side Deadlift
✔️Alternating Overhead DB Press
✔️Double KB March to Single Side Hold March (seriously, try 10 marches holding weight in both hands, then carefully set one weight down and go back to single hold marching. Observe what your body feels and does!)

Happy Tuesday, friend!

I get it. 
Shortcuts are flashy.
They promise quick fixes. 
"All your training problems will be solved!"
They seem too good to be true...
Because they usually are. 

Ultrarunning is *literally* about going the distance.
You can't get there overnight. And honestly, why would you want to?
No "special" supplement can replace patience.
No "secret" exercise can replace hard work.
No "one" workout unlocks your potential.
No "perfect" piece of gear eliminates the need to keep showing up.

It can take months, years, even a decade plus to reach some goals. And around a sport where the whole point is go farther and where we hone skills to endure and thrive under difficult conditions over extended period of times, why would we ever think a quick fix can replace patience, hard work, and working through the process of "becoming?" Not just becoming who you are as an endurance athlete, but what you learn and reveal about yourself as a human. 
I think that's the real gift of this support. 
Becoming more than you ever realized you were or that had inside of you. 
The process reveals...you. Shapes...you. Changes...you. 
Why would you ever want to cheat yourself of that?

Here's to becoming along this wild journey, friends.

I'm loving the balance in training right now. 
I love listening to my body and really hearing what I need.
I love moving. In all the ways. 
Today's strength was so fun.

I addressed hip stability and isometric hamstring strength with these bridges with a press and hold

I worked on legs and anti-rotation with these offset KB Squats

I played with a strong center and a rooted base with these Gorilla rows

I explored lunging and pressing, and how the body tries to compensate for stability with movements like this

I felt energized by these hop back to narrow push ups (do you still like them if we call them burpees?? 😂)

My hips and balance loved the banded glute work in the form of banded knee drives and then banded step backs to lateral step and then to knee drives (if you play music, it's almost like dancing 😉) 

Movement can - and I think should - be play! Strength work is no exception. 

Now, off to a good night's sleep as I have quite a few athletes racing this weekend, and my tracking skills will be in full effect! 💪💪

It's been 5 weeks, and I thought I'd relived all my western states moments over and over in my mind. 

And then, I got this video this morning in my inbox, and all the warmth and magic and happiness flooded me again. 
I knew @jasonkoop was going to have a camera person out to document the day for himself and his athletes, but I never imagined in a million years I'd get footage, too. I finished HOURS after most (ok, all) of his athletes, yet he and @tonyofthehills not only stayed until the end, but then documented those final moments of my #wser100 experience. They didn't have to do that. They didn't have to wait to run me in. I absolutely didn't expect it AT ALL.

It may seem like a small thing, and I bet they didn't even know how much it would mean to me. But oh, it means so much. 
You don't have to win races or be elite to be celebrated or made to feel important. These little details matter. I strive to make every single one of my athletes feel this way, but to be on the receiving end? What an absolute humbling joy it was. 

So thank you, Koop and Tony for this. Truly.  To my amazing support in pacers @carlingu (we finally got footage of our amazing time together!!) @wattsofmiles (congrats on YOUR #neversummer100k finish) and to the incredible  @hrsports and my hubby Brian for running me in at the end. 

I think the most beautiful gift these events give us is not just that we can do hard things, but how much other people show up for us, when we show up for ourselves. ❤️

More often than not, I have people ask me if they can get stronger with limited equipment or space.
My answer is a resounding YES.

Sure, more equipment equals more options and variables to play with, and it's easier to load exercises when you have more to load them with. 
But do not think for a minute that you can't invest in a few pieces of equipment (or even items already around your home) and utilize tempo, appropriate reps/sets, time under tension and a little creativity to challenge yourself and get stronger.

I have a lot of equipment. I mean a LOT. And you best believe I love heavy squats and deadlifts. But time and time again, it's a humble DB or KB I reach for most when it comes to my strength training. Partially because they do give me a great challenge, but also to help break down the barrier to entry some folks may feel when it comes to strength training. The "I don't have enough time, space or equipment, so why bother?" 
Bull crap.
I'm here to show you it's possible.

Use what you have, where you can, when you can. If you find you need more of a challenge or want to explore heavier lifting, super! Plenty of ways to do that and I am here for it!  But if not, then there are options like what I did today: 

Static Lunge with alternating KB pick ups
KB Supported Push Ups 
Kickstand KB RDL
Alternating KB Front Hold Step Up to Lateral Step Up
Box Supported KB Bent Over Rotating Row 
Row Plank 

4x10 of ea/ea side, 60 sec rest between. 

You know I love a good barefoot training session, but when I do wear shoes, I use very flexible, minimal shoes like my zero drop @topoathletic ST-4. Unlike some lifting where a stiff or lifted shoe is desired, I'm looking for a shoe that will give me that barefoot feel while also protecting my feet. This makes sure my the muscles in my feet and lower legs are still doing their "job" and I'm getting lots of feedback from both the ground and my body. When barefoot isn't an option, it's a win, win! 

Here's to going #fartherstronger

Is anyone else coming off an exciting week/weekend of consuming all things UTMB?

UTMB, like many of the big races, reminds us that big challenges await us out there. And it's so inspiring as we watch others accomplish incredible things. We see what is possible. You needn't be Courtney or Jim or even run events like UTMB (but it's awesome if you want to!) to put yourself out there and chase a crazy goal or idea. To dream big.

But if you have a big G Goal, you have to find the strength in yourself to go for it. You have to trust in your ability to put in the work. You also have to have the courage to try, despite no guarantee that things will go the way you hope. 
Big goals lie at a crazy little intersection where preparation meets opportunity. It's on the same street as hard work and being vulnerable, neighbors with humility and optimism.
Nothing worth chasing ever comes easy or is guaranteed. I think that's why big goals scare us and excite us so much. We grow in the proportion in which we challenge ourselves to expand. And that growth is never wasted nor can it be taken away from us.

Strength Training - We know it's good for us, but for as many reasons as there are TO strength train, there are as are many reasons people have for not starting a strength program.  

I think this is a case of "done is better than perfect."

Don't have enough equipment? Get creative and use what you have on hand, invest in some simple pieces, or even join a gym. 

Not sure what to do or if your form is correct? Higher a trainer or strength coach to go over a program that will work for you, and do form checks to make sure you are doing things correctly. 

Find it boring? Meet with a buddy or start with classes with strength coaches that know their stuff. 

Find it complicated? Remember the basics WORK. It's all about resistance and loading appropriately, not exercises being "fancy." So work on squat, hinge, pushing, pulling, lunging, (anti)rotation and carrying. 

Don't have time? 30-45 min is great, but 10-20 min is better than nothing. This is not an all or nothing prospect. Done is better than perfect. 

With training in general, it's amazing what you can do if you focus on doing what you can with what you have and where you are. 

Let's go!

Next time you approach your strength training, don't sleep on the benefits of strategic pauses and time under tension. In this case, I'm showing how you can incorporate this with some lower body exercises and specifially loading the quads. This type of loading is helpful for runners and cyclists (when paired with an appropriate training program) and is great if you don't have a lot of external weight to load or challenge yourself with. (but you can still absolutely use these strategies if you do!)

We've got:

"1 and 1/4" heel elevated rack hold squats - the rack hold and elevated heels really put an emphasis on the quads, and the 1/4 up from the bottom to back down before you return to start really loads the leg like something you have to feel to believe. Have a squat rack and a bar? Try this as a front BB front squat.

Front Lunge to hold - Step forward into a Lunge and then perform 3-5 reps before holding at the bottom for a 3 count. Repeat 2 more times for ea round. 

Rear foot elevated Hops with pause - like the lunges above, complete 3-5 hops and then pause at the bottom for a count of three. That pause eliminates momentum and challenges the legs. 

Then, when you're all done, a nice little stretch. This may look like a typical runner's Lunge, but what you can't see is me thinking about dragging my front leg heel back (but not moving thay heel!) as I gently push forward with my rear knee. This helps to really target and  open things up in hip extension. Raising the arm helps create more stretch and "openness" with the area we are targeting.

Finally, a little quad braced Deadbug action. Using my @stickmobility I'm pressing INTO the stick with my quads while simultaneously resisting this force. Maintain this tension as you extend one leg slowly at a time. Exhale fully with each extension. Keep your low back in contact with the ground the entire time. 

I invite you to try one (or a few!) of these as appropriate with your next strength session. 💪

Race week (or month) nerves. They are so normal.
Have you done enough the past months leading up to the big day? Has there been a sudden change in the forecast? A last-minute course change? A "what was I thinking when I signed?!? loop playing in your head?
A healthy dose of pre-race nerves is good. It means you respect the task at hand & are in an elevated state for action. It means you care & are excited. (Excited is good!)
But if pre-race panic or anxiety are wearing heaving on you as race day approaches? A few things to consider:

👉 review your training from the blocks leading up to the event. See all of the work you have put in, & objectively view your preparation. Seeing your training laid out like this can help you perhaps put a "rough week" you had more recently in perspective compared to the solid months you have been training. 
👉 now look back farther. Not just the past 6 months, but the past 36-60 months. All of your training has built upon the block before it. The foundation for the race you're about to embark on was probably laid well before you even considered or signed up for it. Think of your athletic development with a long lens & not a microscope. 
👉 be realistic. Having said all of the above, sometimes training doesn't go as we'd hoped. A lot of time off for sickness, family emergencies, missed time for injury, changes in jobs...it happens. In these cases, it's good to reevaluate your expectations for your event. This doesn't mean throw your goals out the window, but perhaps just adjust them so you're setting yourself up for success with your A, B and C goals with where you are showing up on race day. This can take pressure off & allow you to enjoy the day for what it is & not what "could have been."
👉 focus on rest, reducing as much stress as possible & quality fueling race week (better yet, the 2 weeks before). We can't control everything, but try and stack the deck in your favor by not overextendeding yourself in the final weeks before you toe the start line, & prioritize rest & quality foods.
👉trust yourself & your training. You have done a lot of hard work to get here. You can do hard things. Don't forget to have FUN out there!

Often, when you are a coach, your perceived value in your profession by some is (incorrectly) based on your athletic accomplishments.The good coaches & wise athletes know this not to be true, but so many young coaches (in both age and/or experience) can't separate their performances & their value & capability as a coach. 
I, too, felt early in my coaching career that I needed to "prove" I was worth hiring because I could "do" the things...qualify for the special race, run a certain time, place a certain way. I quickly learned that none of that made me more valuable as a coach. Certainly, the experience at certain events gave me great insight to share with athletes, but in no way was my experience going to ever mirror theirs. It can help with logistics and the "nitty gritty" of a course, but my time at an event & my placing there in no way made me a better coach. 

I am not saying that you can't aim to be both a great athlete & coach yourself. But I do feel very strongly that there is zero correlation between being a "great" athlete and a "great" coach. Some of the very best coaches I know & admire greatly were never podium finishers or out there breaking records. They sure did know how to be damn amazing coaches, though. 

Being a great coach is about learning, listening, mentoring, growing. It's about working on your coaching skills & flexing your coach muscles just like you would your physical muscles. I am so thankful I have had many different experiences with athletes through the nearly 20 years I have been coaching; from mixed martial arts, to football players, to strength based athletes, to runners and cyclists, to name a few. Each and every one of these experiences allowed me to hone & improve my coaching as well as to learn from some of the best of the best in each industry. These are simply lessons learned that you can't get unless you are a fully committed to the art and joy of coaching.

If you only value your performance as the basis of your value as a coach, you're just an injury or passage of time away from being obsolete. However, being an outstanding coach can be a legacy that far outlives any personal performance.💪

Pssst... here's a little "secret."

If you have a summer race next year, yes, NOW is the time to start laying the fitness foundation that you will build on for the months to come. The fitter you get earlier in the season, the better you set yourself up for success to get the most out of all the things to come.
I'm not saying training will be easy... but you will have a LOT less friction and playing catch up when it comes to getting the most of your training. 
Course correcting won't be as big of a deal.
A longer runway building fitness results in less "cramming" of training (often resulting in injury and panic) and better adaptation from different training stimulus. 
You instill consistency early, which is KEY.
And if you're fit when you start the specificity part of training for your event, you'll be able to get the most out of it. 👏

So start now. Your future self will thank you!

A gentle reminder that strength training has a place in your training lineup, and if you have been thinking about it, maybe 2024 is the year you are going to make it happen (or recommit to it).

It doesn't have to look pretty; around here, sometimes that means showing up in a hoodie in a cold, cluttered garage on a January morning, and It doesn't have to be fancy or include a lot of equipment (I try to show how you can do less with more, more often than not).

But I am here to say if you care about form, effective training, looking for a few ways to think outside the training box, and want to be a more durable runner AND human...welcome! I am glad you are here 🙂

Today's session included:
Elevated pigeon rocking (hip mobility)
TRX Sprinter Start with a pause (hip flexion and extension, balance, glutes)
Banded TRX Frog Bridge (hamstrings (esp medial), glutes, abductors)
TRX Rear Foot Elevated Lunge with Pulse Hold (balance, quads, hip drive)
Front Rack Banded Toe Tap (balance, stability, glutes, lateral hips)

I am making my new space my own and loving the process. I hope you will enjoy watching it evolve as well!

In my nearly 20 years of coaching (with over a decade of ultrarunning specific coaching as part of that time) I have evolved more & more as a coach, & made decisions that I *personally* felt represented myself & my approach to coaching best. Here are a few things (many of which I once did) that I now choose NOT to do in my coaching practice:
✔️Write static plans.I have nothing against static plans, per se. They can be a GREAT entry level (& cost effective) way for many of those looking to start training & not knowing where to start (that is what I did before I worked with my first coach!) or can be a template that more experienced athletes can riff off of & adapt to fit their needs. I have chosen not to write or sell static plans, however, as my greatest joy & purpose, & what I feel brings the most value & benefit to my athletes as a coach, is the relationship I make with my athletes. We become a collaboration, & the magic of their training comes from working together, adjusting things, and finding what works for them.That is COACHING vs programming.
✔️Posting up my race times and splits. No heat for those that do this; it has just been a personal decision as my race times have zero all to do with my ability to coach someone else, & I don't feel they have any relevance. Plus, we all know how ultrasignup works; if someone wants to know my time (or anyone else's) it's out there. As far as my workout splits? Baby, I left road racing years ago & I focus on RPE vs pace, so my pace means jack 💩. 😂
✔️This is simple; if I don't feel like an athlete or I are a good fit and they would flourish under someone else, I am going to find them that fit. I would never hold an athlete back due to stubborness or ego.
✔️I take rest days. I choose not to streak. I will cut a training session if something is wrong & I know conituning is crossing the line of "training" vs "obsession." I don't promote "no pain, no gain." Do I want you to push limit & grow as an athlete? ABSOLUTELY. But never at the cost of honoring or listening to ones body. 
✔️I will never push an athlete towards a goal because it is what I want. I WILL support the shit out of my athletes and THEIR goals.

As ultrarunners, we tend to just want to run - a lot, right? Who has time for anything else?!
I do believe making the time for strength training is important. 👇
Strength training not only has a host of benefits for ultra runners; with everything from improved balance, mobility, and increased muscle fibers and tendon strength/health as well as overall power, but there is also the "durability as a human factor;" as someone who was diagnosed with osteopenia in my early 20's, strength training is a non-negotiable for me. All the running in the world wasn't going to help my bone density like heavy lifting did, and working on my balance, proprioception, and mobility helped me be less likely to fall and hurt myself. Just because I have normal bone density for my age now (something I am VERY proud of) doesn't mean the work stops. While it isn't the cure all for every running issue and won't guarantee that you can avoid injuries, it sure can help strengthen your human machine for the rough and tumble demands of ultra running and life.
When it comes to strength, start where you are. If you don't have BBs and DBs, start with BW and bands. Build from there. Don't let a lack of certain tools keep you from using the ones you DO have. Ask questions. Meet with a trainer if you need help with form. Follow people (hopefully I am one of them) that educates you on strength training, inspires you with new ideas, and help lower the barrier of feeling like "it's one more thing to add" to making it be something that is accessible and that you  can prioritize - esp in the transition and early seasons.
Here we have: 
Balance Board Work
Standing Soleus Calf Raises

then some fun "like" supersets of:
DB Bent Over Rows and TRX Inverted Rows
BB Heel Elevated Front Squats and TRX Pistol Squats
BB RDLs and TRX Glute Bridges
These "like" sets can be done together which is its own fun challenge; I like to do the weighted set heavier (4x6 or 5x5) and the TRX version in the more endurance range (3x10-12). Or, they can be done separately based on your equipment access. You can get creative given your situation or equipment availability.

When I say I could write 20 slides on this...I am not joking.

But since we have to start somewhere...here are 9 things I wish more runners knew about strength training.

💪Don't be afraid to lift heavy, esp in your "off" and early seasons. Lifting heavy challenges your body in the best of ways and is one of the best way to give your body the stimulus it needs for adaptation, and allows you to build critical strength and power. Plus, it feels good/empowering. And no, ladies, it won't bulk you up. Aim for a weight that allows you to maintain good form, but 1-2 reps in the tank (not to failure)
💪You don't have to spend hours in the gym. 45-60 min (and in some cases shorter) sessions can give you a lot of bang for your buck, with the right programming.
💪When it comes to balancing out and enhancing your running, in most cases 2-3 full body days is all you need for most of your season
💪It doesn't have to be complicated. Focus on the key movement patterns; Squat, Hinge, Lunge, Push, Pull and (anti) Rotation
💪The best ways to adjust your training through the season to work WITH (not against) your run volume and training is to adjust volume (reps/sets) intensity, exercise selection, tempo and rest based on your goals
💪 Running is basically a single leg sport, over and over and over again. As such, don't skimp on your unilateral training
💪Fasted Training - Please, just don't. You need to fuel before and after your strength sessions.You won't get the most out of them or recover from them in a depleted state
💪Although it can be FUN to have variety, you don't need a lot of space or equipment to reap the benefits of strength training. Don't let the lack of either stop you from getting started! As you get stronger, you can invest in more equipment (or that gym membership)
💪It's totally ok to want to train for performance and aesthetics. You like to lift because you like the way your shoulders pop or how your butt looks in your running tights? Nothing wrong with that. Those muscles are workhorses, and it's fun to see how strength training shapes our bodies.

Exploring the eccentric.

No, not the weird and wonderful that makes you, you.
But Eccentric loading and how it has its place in a runner's strength programming.

The eccentric phase of a muscle contraction is when it  l e n g t h e n s (vs the concentric where is shortens, like the curl portion of a bicep curl, and isometric where there is contraction but no joint movement; think a static hold).

The eccentric phase of an exercise, especially when done at a slower and controlled tempo and loaded appropriately, creates force and micro damage to the muscles, which in turns leads to greater muscle development, durability and strength as the body responds to this stimulus and repairs accordingly (i.e. increased muscle tissue and stronger ligaments and tendons). This *can* lead to increased soreness following eccentric exercises, as anyone that has done tempo squats or a lot of downhill running will attest to.

While it is not a replacement for run specificity, eccentric training in the gym can be a tool in a runner's tool kit (esp for those that lack a lot of down hill exposure) to help prepare the legs for the demands of downhill running in particular. Some refer to this as "seasoning" the quads, which is a nice way of saying "causes micro damage in the gym so your body will respond by creating stronger and more durable leg muscles."
Tomato-tomhato.

Some examples of eccentric loading are:

Tempo Slider Reverse Lunges
Tempo RDLs 
Tempo Bulgarian Split Squats (why YES that is my soul leaving my body you see there, not the fact I was training in a 29F garage) 
3-4 Count Squats (the lower is the focus here!)
Single Leg Slider Bridge Extensions
Bulgarian Split Squats Hops (Please, someone save me at this point).

While this is far from exhaustive of a list of exercises or the benefits of eccentric training in general, I hope this gives you an idea of things you can try and why they might be helpful for you, my trail and ultra running friend.

It's that time of the year when many people are looking to work with a coach; whether it is because they go into their "once in a lifetime" dream race, or maybe last year's season didn;t go as they hoped and they want some outside help/perspective, or maybe you are brand new to ultrarunning and want to team up with a professional to help you navigate your first race.
With so many coaches out there, it can be hard to find the one. Maybe it's someone you have been following for a while, or maybe you have reached out to a company like @cts_ultrarunning and have been set up with a few coach consults. 
One of the things I hear the most when I am doing a coach consult and speaking to a prospective athlete is "I don't know what I should ask!" And I get it! So let me give you some ideas of what to ask that potential coach you are going to chat with to see if they are the right fit for you. 

➡️What does communication look like when working with you? How often will we talk or be in contact? How often and how will I receive feedback? What are the channels of communication (talk/text/zoom etc)? This is important to know so your expectation of coach contact aligns with how your coach executes this part of your coaching. Also, and this is important, the coach you work with should be someone you want to talk to and feel comfortable with. The coach/ athlete relationship is just that - a relationship. So start there. Is this someone I want to have on my team?

➡️What are you looking at and for when reviewing my training? How are you seeing my data (are they using a platform like Training Peaks or Final Surge that provides data and metrics, or a spreadsheet)? What kind of feedback are you looking for from me (the athlete)?

➡️How are you measuring and tracking progress? How will YOU know that I am on the right track for my event or goals?

➡️If you are looking for additional support in areas like strength training or nutrition, do they a) offer this and b) if they do, do they have the appropriate certifications or degrees to provide this as part of your coaching? Does it come as part of your training package or is there any additional investment?
